04957nam a22006255i 9780822390183DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20072007ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223901837 a10.1515/97808223901832doi  a(DE-B1597)553637  a(OCoLC)1224279131  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aHQ1715.5b.Z37 2007 7aSOC0100002bisacsh1 aŽarkov, Dubravka, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Body of War :bMedia, Ethnicity, and Gender in the Break-up of Yugoslavia /cDubravka Žarkov; ed. by Robyn Wiegman, Caren Kaplan. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2007] 4c©2007  a1 online resource (296 p.) :b15 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aNext Wave: New Directions in Women's Studies : 4400tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tPART I. THE MATERNAL BODY -- t1. The Whore against the Mother of All Serbs -- t2. Pictures of the Wall of Love -- t3. Troubles with Motherhood -- tPART II. THE VICTIMIZED BODY -- t4. The Body of All Serbs -- t5. All the Bodies of Croatia -- t6. Sexual Geographies of Ethnicity -- t7. On Victims and Villains -- t8. The Body of the Other Man -- t9. Troubles with the Victim -- tPART III. THE ARMED BODY -- t10. Soldiers of Tradition -- t11. Troubles with Arms -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn The Body of War, Dubravka Žarkov analyzes representations of female and male bodies in the Croatian and Serbian press in the late 1980s and in the early 1990s, during the war in which Yugoslavia disintegrated. Žarkov proposes that the Balkan war was not a war between ethnic groups; rather, ethnicity was produced by the war itself. Žarkov explores the process through which ethnicity was generated, showing how lived and symbolic female and male bodies became central to it. She does not posit a direct causal relationship between hate speech published in the press during the mid-1980s and the acts of violence in the war. Instead, she argues that both the representational practices of the “media war” and the violent practices of the “ethnic war” depended on specific, shared notions of femininity and masculinity, norms of (hetero)sexuality, and definitions of ethnicity.Tracing the links between the war and press representations of ethnicity, gender, and sexuality, Žarkov examines the media’s coverage of two major protests by women who explicitly identified themselves as mothers, of sexual violence against women and men during the war, and of women as militants. She draws on contemporary feminist analyses of violence to scrutinize international and local feminist writings on the war in former Yugoslavia. Demonstrating that some of the same essentialist ideas of gender and sexuality used to produce and reinforce the significance of ethnic differences during the war often have been invoked by feminists, she points out the political and theoretical drawbacks to grounding feminist strategies against violence in ideas of female victimhood.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aEthnicityzFormer Yugoslav republics. 0aKosovo War, 1998-1999. 0aMass media and warzFormer Yugoslav republics. 0aNationalismzFormer Yugoslav republics. 0aWomen and warzFormer Yugoslav republics. 0aWomen in mass media. 0aYugoslav War, 1991-1995xWomen. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Feminism & Feminist Theory.2bisacsh1 aKaplan, Caren, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aWiegman, Robyn, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822390183zC